# Project Conventions

> This file layers on top of the code4me plugin's baseline guidance. Plugin-shipped guidance (language references, the canonical workflow, the ethos) applies generically; **project-specific rules in this file authoritatively override** when the two conflict.
>
> Treat this file like code: review it when the agent surprises you, prune regularly, keep it under ~200 lines.

## Project shape

<!-- One-line stack summary. Examples:
- "Go 1.22 microservice handling Stripe webhooks; deployed via ArgoCD to k8s; owner: #team-billing."
- "Unity 2022.3 LTS multiplayer game; C#/.NET 4.x scripting; PlayFab backend; iOS/Android targets."
- "Next.js 14 app router; Postgres via Drizzle; Vercel deployment; team of 3." -->

PLACEHOLDER — describe the stack, deployment, owners.

## Run / Build / Test

<!-- The bash commands an agent should know. Single-test runners are particularly valuable. -->

- `make dev` — start the dev environment
- `make test` — run unit tests
- `make test-integration` — run integration tests (requires X)
- `make lint` — run linters; must pass before commit
- Single test: `<command>` — invoke a single test by name

## Layout

<!-- Key directories and what lives in each. Don't enumerate every folder — list the load-bearing ones plus any with non-obvious purpose. -->

- `<dir>/` — purpose; do most work here
- `<dir>/generated/` — generated code; never hand-edit
- `<dir>/scripts/` — operator scripts; not production code

## Conventions

<!-- Project-specific rules that aren't enforced by linters. Be specific. -->

- Errors: prefer `<pattern>`; avoid `<antipattern>`
- Logging: structured (`<library>`); never `println`/`fmt.Println`/`console.log`
- Tests: table-driven style; canonical example at `<path>`
- HTTP/RPC handlers: `<return shape>`
- Async / concurrency: `<pattern preference>`

## Boundaries

<!-- Never-edit paths, scope limits, dependency policies. -->

- Never edit `<path>` (auto-generated)
- Adding a new dependency requires `<process>`
- Don't modify `<surface>` without coordinating with `<owner>`

## Gotchas

<!-- The surprising things — environment quirks, hidden coupling, "this caught me." -->

- `<surprising thing about the environment>`
- `<hidden coupling between modules>`
- `<test fixture or env var that's mandatory but easy to miss>`

## Available MCPs

<!-- Declared MCPs and when each subagent should prefer them.
     If you ran /code4me-init with the recommended MCP starter, list what's there.
     Document preferences per subagent — the orchestrator's Context Pack reminds subagents
     to prefer MCPs over Read/Grep when an MCP serves the task. -->

- **`<mcp-name>`** — `<purpose>`. Subagents should prefer this MCP for `<query type>`.

## Multi-language layout (delete if single-language)

<!-- If this is a heterogeneous project, layer additional CLAUDE.md files under
     language-specific directories. The plugin's language references provide the
     baseline; per-language CLAUDE.md adds project-specific overlay. -->

```
your-project/
├── CLAUDE.md            # this file — common conventions
├── src/
│   ├── csharp/CLAUDE.md # C# specifics: your DI, Unity quirks, naming exceptions
│   ├── swift/CLAUDE.md  # Swift specifics: your SwiftUI patterns
│   ├── cpp/CLAUDE.md    # C++ specifics: standard version, exception policy
│   └── python/CLAUDE.md # Python specifics: framework choice, type-strictness
```

## Cross-vendor pairing (code4me v0.7+)

<!-- If you want cross-vendor pairing on by default for this project, declare it here.
     Otherwise, enable per-milestone at intake time. -->

- **Default**: single-vendor (Claude). Cross-vendor is opt-in per milestone.
- **Enabling at intake**: state "enable cross-vendor pairing" or "use the alternation policy" in your milestone description; the orchestrator will apply `references/cross-vendor-policy.md`.
- **Setup**: see README "External agents (Codex)" — requires `codex` CLI on PATH and `OPENAI_API_KEY` configured.
